Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=703257" target="_blank">Yash Pal Singh</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            As someone who spent 41 years in IIT Kharagpur, 4+1 as a student, and 36 years as a faculty member (1956 to 1997), I am dismayed by this controversy. I do not want to get into a debate on Hinduism or the caste system as that should not be the focal point of my comments. Although the IITs have remained beyond the shadow of the political parties for all these decades, one must not jump to a conclusion that the IIT students were isolated from every thought process. <br/>
Please note that because the IIT system was not 'infected' by the 'professional politicians' IIT Kharagpur was the only Institute in West Bengal that continued its academic activities without any major disruption.<br/>
We had the Technology Students Gymkhana constituted by elected (no foothold was given to any political party) representative of the Student Body who were responsible for organizing Cultural, Literary, and Sports activities. The Bengali, English, and Hindi debating societies both at the Institute level as well as at the Hall of Residence level, were lively venues for intellectual expression.  Same was the case for the various Dramatic societies. <br/>
We had some informal groups of faculty and students from a particular State, but they organized cultural get-together where all others were invited and exposed to their rich culture and delicacies. In no case they stood for any narrow sectarian view.<br/>
The Institute did not, repeat DID NOT, have any "Group" representing a narrow sub-group of any hue. All debating fora were open to everyone -- students as well as the faculty and staff -- so no ground was given to any narrow group to propagate their views as those of the IIT student body. I feel that the initial mistake of IIT Madras was to recognize such groups -- may be the decision was influenced by the political ambiance in that State. I strongly feel that none of the IITs should give official recognition to any sectarian group of any hue -- left, right, or center. Pray leave these hallowed Institutes alone -- as it is the average student and faculty member has plenty on his plate. Please let them aim to excel in peace.
                         </div>



