                            This verbose article by Rukmini B. Nair states a lot but conveys little. I would like to raise some points on this whole episode.<br/>
1)	When a student enters a University or Institute for further studies, does he/she not agree to play by certain agreed rules and regulations of the said educational "body"?  If these rules are violated by the students, then does this violation constitute "freedom of expression" and is not the "body" within its right to ban such violation? In this instance, the IIT Madras has apparently taken exception not because of the contents of the pamphlets but only temporarily banned the said group for violation of the agreed rules, that such groups do not use the name of the Institute for their activities, anonymous letters or not. In what way is the IIT wrong on this?<br/><br/>
2)	If the pamphlets contain material that is condemning a particular religion in general (in this case "Hinduism"} and hurting the sentiments of its followers, in addition to and not limited to censoring certain decadent social practices associated with it (in this case casteism), then is this  not "spreading hatred" against the religion and is spreading such hatred permitted in the Constitution? Would not the so called secularists make a hue and cry had this condemnation been on Islam and Christianity in general?<br/>
It is one thing to discuss, argue, agree or dissent etc. in Universities but it is another thing to vilify and spread hatred.
